ript (ca. 1000) is essentially the work of one poet who composed it circa 700. Of course, during the poem's written transmission, several hundred scribal errors crept into its text. These errors are interpreted in the central chapters of the book as valuable evidence for language history, cultural change, and scribal practice. Neidorf's analysis reveals that the scribes earnestly attempted to standardize and modernize the text's orthography, but their unfamiliarity with obsolete words and ancient heroes resulted in frequent errors. The Beowulf manuscript thus emerges from his study as an indispensible witness to processes of linguistic and cultural change that took place in England between the eighth and eleventh centuries. An appendix addresses J. R. R. Tolkien's Beowulf: A Translation and Commentary, which was published in 2014. Neidorf assesses Tolkien's general views on the transmission of Beowulf and evaluates his position on various textual issues.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aEpic poetry, English (Old)xCriticism, Textual. 0aLanguage and culturezEnglandxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aTransmission of textszEnglandxHistoryyTo 1500. 4aFolklore. 4aPoetry & Criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook Package 2017z978311062534908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell Univ. Press eBook-Package Pilot Project 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501708282423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501708282.jpg  a978-3-11-060674-4  Cornell Univ. Press eBook-Package Pilot Project 2014-2015c2014d2015  a978-3-11-062534-9  COR eBook Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL